3. cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition): Although the paper does not explicitly mention computer vision, the proposed model can be applied to image data represented as graphs, which is a common problem in computer vision. 
4. cs.CL (Computation and Language): The paper evaluates the proposed model on a semi-supervised document classification task, which is a natural language processing problem. 
5. cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing): The proposed model is a neural network architecture that uses feedback-looped filters, which is a type of graph filter that can be applied universally to any graph without knowing its structure.
